<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="377" type="redescription">
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="377">Redescription.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="377">Measurements (4 males, 9 females). Body length (from apex of head to tip of forewings): male 10.6-11.4 mm, female 12.9-13.9 mm; head length (from apex of cephalic process to base of eyes): male 1.25-1.33 mm, female 1.35-1.45 mm; head width (including eyes): male 1.30-1.43 mm, female 1.50-1.60 mm; forewing length: male 8.5-9.1 mm, female 10.3-11.4 mm.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="377">
Coloration. General coloration as in generic description (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Habitus of Orthopagus species. (A, B) O. bartletti sp. n., male, holotype, Karnataka, India; (C, D) O. exoletus (Melichar), male and female, Sri Lanka; (E, F) O. hainanensis sp. n., male and female, paratypes, Hainan, China; (G, H) O. lunulifer Uhler, male and female, China; (I, J) O. philippinus Melichar, male and female, Philippines; (K, L) O. splendens (Germar), male and female, China." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.94.26859.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/221398" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">2I-J</figureCitation>
). Vertex predominantly dark brown, lateral margins with a pale ochraceous S-shaped streak in posterior three quarters (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Orthopagus philippinus Melichar. (A) Head, pronotum and mesonotum, dorsal view. (B) Head and pronotum, lateral view. (C) Head and pronotum, ventral view. (D) Male segment X and pygofer, dorsal view. (E) Male pygofer, gonostyles, and segment X, lateral view. (F) Male pygofer and gonostyles, caudal view. (G) Gonostyle; (H) Aedeagus, dorsal view. (I) Aedeagus, lateral view. (J) Aedeagus, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.94.26859.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/221406" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">9A</figureCitation>
). Frons light ochraceous with small dark brown spots along intermediate and lateral carinae and a large roundish dark brown spot at base (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Orthopagus philippinus Melichar. (A) Head, pronotum and mesonotum, dorsal view. (B) Head and pronotum, lateral view. (C) Head and pronotum, ventral view. (D) Male segment X and pygofer, dorsal view. (E) Male pygofer, gonostyles, and segment X, lateral view. (F) Male pygofer and gonostyles, caudal view. (G) Gonostyle; (H) Aedeagus, dorsal view. (I) Aedeagus, lateral view. (J) Aedeagus, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.94.26859.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/221406" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">9C</figureCitation>
). Forewing membrane pattern as in Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Forewing of Orthopagus species. (A) O. bartletti sp. n.; (B) O. exoletus (Melichar); (C) O. hainanensis sp. n.; (D) O. lunulifer Uhler; (E) O. philippinus Melichar; (F) O. splendens (Germar)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.94.26859.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/221399" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">3E</figureCitation>
. Hind wing membrane with a narrow dark brown infuscation along the apical portion of CuA1 vein, not extending along hind wing apical margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="377">
Structure. Head with cephalic process moderately elongate (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Orthopagus philippinus Melichar. (A) Head, pronotum and mesonotum, dorsal view. (B) Head and pronotum, lateral view. (C) Head and pronotum, ventral view. (D) Male segment X and pygofer, dorsal view. (E) Male pygofer, gonostyles, and segment X, lateral view. (F) Male pygofer and gonostyles, caudal view. (G) Gonostyle; (H) Aedeagus, dorsal view. (I) Aedeagus, lateral view. (J) Aedeagus, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.94.26859.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/221406" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">9A-B</figureCitation>
). Vertex (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Orthopagus philippinus Melichar. (A) Head, pronotum and mesonotum, dorsal view. (B) Head and pronotum, lateral view. (C) Head and pronotum, ventral view. (D) Male segment X and pygofer, dorsal view. (E) Male pygofer, gonostyles, and segment X, lateral view. (F) Male pygofer and gonostyles, caudal view. (G) Gonostyle; (H) Aedeagus, dorsal view. (I) Aedeagus, lateral view. (J) Aedeagus, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.94.26859.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/221406" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">9A</figureCitation>
) with ratio of length at midline to width between eyes 1.6-1.8. Transition of vertex to frons blunt, broadly rounded in lateral view, cephalic process thus appearing inflated and bulbous apically (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Orthopagus philippinus Melichar. (A) Head, pronotum and mesonotum, dorsal view. (B) Head and pronotum, lateral view. (C) Head and pronotum, ventral view. (D) Male segment X and pygofer, dorsal view. (E) Male pygofer, gonostyles, and segment X, lateral view. (F) Male pygofer and gonostyles, caudal view. (G) Gonostyle; (H) Aedeagus, dorsal view. (I) Aedeagus, lateral view. (J) Aedeagus, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.94.26859.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/221406" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">9B</figureCitation>
). Frons relatively narrow, with ratio of length at midline to maximum width 2.7-3.1.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="377">
Male genitalia. Pygofer, in lateral view, with dorso-posterior margin produced into a relatively large but narrow, tooth-like, apically obtuse process (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Orthopagus philippinus Melichar. (A) Head, pronotum and mesonotum, dorsal view. (B) Head and pronotum, lateral view. (C) Head and pronotum, ventral view. (D) Male segment X and pygofer, dorsal view. (E) Male pygofer, gonostyles, and segment X, lateral view. (F) Male pygofer and gonostyles, caudal view. (G) Gonostyle; (H) Aedeagus, dorsal view. (I) Aedeagus, lateral view. (J) Aedeagus, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.94.26859.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/221406" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">9E</figureCitation>
); in ventral view (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Orthopagus philippinus Melichar. (A) Head, pronotum and mesonotum, dorsal view. (B) Head and pronotum, lateral view. (C) Head and pronotum, ventral view. (D) Male segment X and pygofer, dorsal view. (E) Male pygofer, gonostyles, and segment X, lateral view. (F) Male pygofer and gonostyles, caudal view. (G) Gonostyle; (H) Aedeagus, dorsal view. (I) Aedeagus, lateral view. (J) Aedeagus, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.94.26859.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/221406" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">9F</figureCitation>
) much longer than in dorsal view (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Orthopagus philippinus Melichar. (A) Head, pronotum and mesonotum, dorsal view. (B) Head and pronotum, lateral view. (C) Head and pronotum, ventral view. (D) Male segment X and pygofer, dorsal view. (E) Male pygofer, gonostyles, and segment X, lateral view. (F) Male pygofer and gonostyles, caudal view. (G) Gonostyle; (H) Aedeagus, dorsal view. (I) Aedeagus, lateral view. (J) Aedeagus, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.94.26859.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/221406" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">9D</figureCitation>
) with ratio of ventral to dorsal width about 2.5. Gonostyles (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Orthopagus philippinus Melichar. (A) Head, pronotum and mesonotum, dorsal view. (B) Head and pronotum, lateral view. (C) Head and pronotum, ventral view. (D) Male segment X and pygofer, dorsal view. (E) Male pygofer, gonostyles, and segment X, lateral view. (F) Male pygofer and gonostyles, caudal view. (G) Gonostyle; (H) Aedeagus, dorsal view. (I) Aedeagus, lateral view. (J) Aedeagus, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.94.26859.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/221406" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">9G</figureCitation>
) large, broad medially, with dorsal margin weakly sinuate. Aedeagus (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Orthopagus philippinus Melichar. (A) Head, pronotum and mesonotum, dorsal view. (B) Head and pronotum, lateral view. (C) Head and pronotum, ventral view. (D) Male segment X and pygofer, dorsal view. (E) Male pygofer, gonostyles, and segment X, lateral view. (F) Male pygofer and gonostyles, caudal view. (G) Gonostyle; (H) Aedeagus, dorsal view. (I) Aedeagus, lateral view. (J) Aedeagus, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.94.26859.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/221406" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">9H-J</figureCitation>
) with endosomal processes covered with minute superficial spines, extended posteriad and strongly curved laterad and dorso-anteriad but not reaching the base of phallobase; phallobase with one pair of large, strongly inflated dorsolateral lobes, their apex convergent and tapering posteriad (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Orthopagus philippinus Melichar. (A) Head, pronotum and mesonotum, dorsal view. (B) Head and pronotum, lateral view. (C) Head and pronotum, ventral view. (D) Male segment X and pygofer, dorsal view. (E) Male pygofer, gonostyles, and segment X, lateral view. (F) Male pygofer and gonostyles, caudal view. (G) Gonostyle; (H) Aedeagus, dorsal view. (I) Aedeagus, lateral view. (J) Aedeagus, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.94.26859.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/221406" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">9I</figureCitation>
), and one pair of smaller, thumb-like ventral lobes, directed ventro-posteriad (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Orthopagus philippinus Melichar. (A) Head, pronotum and mesonotum, dorsal view. (B) Head and pronotum, lateral view. (C) Head and pronotum, ventral view. (D) Male segment X and pygofer, dorsal view. (E) Male pygofer, gonostyles, and segment X, lateral view. (F) Male pygofer and gonostyles, caudal view. (G) Gonostyle; (H) Aedeagus, dorsal view. (I) Aedeagus, lateral view. (J) Aedeagus, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.94.26859.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/221406" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">9I-J</figureCitation>
). Segment X, in lateral view, relatively narrow basally, widening to apex beyond middle, apex blunt (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Orthopagus philippinus Melichar. (A) Head, pronotum and mesonotum, dorsal view. (B) Head and pronotum, lateral view. (C) Head and pronotum, ventral view. (D) Male segment X and pygofer, dorsal view. (E) Male pygofer, gonostyles, and segment X, lateral view. (F) Male pygofer and gonostyles, caudal view. (G) Gonostyle; (H) Aedeagus, dorsal view. (I) Aedeagus, lateral view. (J) Aedeagus, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.94.26859.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/221406" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">9E</figureCitation>
); in dorsal view, relatively large and broad, widest in apical third, ratio of length to maximum width 1.0-1.1 (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Orthopagus philippinus Melichar. (A) Head, pronotum and mesonotum, dorsal view. (B) Head and pronotum, lateral view. (C) Head and pronotum, ventral view. (D) Male segment X and pygofer, dorsal view. (E) Male pygofer, gonostyles, and segment X, lateral view. (F) Male pygofer and gonostyles, caudal view. (G) Gonostyle; (H) Aedeagus, dorsal view. (I) Aedeagus, lateral view. (J) Aedeagus, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.94.26859.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/221406" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">9D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="377">Female genitalia as in generic description.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="377" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="377">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="377">So far only known from the Luzon island, Philippines.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="377" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="377">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="377">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Melichar" authorityYear="1914" class="Insecta" family="Dictyopharidae" genus="Orthopagus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Orthopagus philippinus" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="philippinus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">Orthopagus philippinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily recognized from other species of the genus by the shape of the head and the presence of a relatively large roundish dark spot at base of frons which is present in all specimens studied.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="377">
<bibRefCitation author="Melichar, L" journalOrPublisher="Philippine Journal of Science" pageId="12" pageNumber="381" pagination="173 - 181" refId="B22" refString="Melichar, L, 1914. Neue Homopteren von den Philippinen. Philippine Journal of Science 9: 173 - 181" title="Neue Homopteren von den Philippinen." volume="9" year="1914">Melichar (1914)</bibRefCitation>
indicated that he described this species based on five (male and female) specimens from &quot;Luzon, Los 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Baños">Banos</normalizedToken>
, Mt. Maquiling (C. F. Baker)&quot;. Six specimens (1 male, 5 females) preserved in Melichar personal collection in MMBC and labelled as either from Los 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Baños">Banos</normalizedToken>
or Mt. Makiling and collected by Baker are considered here as the original syntypes. The male specimen is designated here as the lectotype for 
<taxonomicName genus="O." lsidName="O. philippinus" pageId="8" pageNumber="377" rank="species" species="philippinus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">O. philippinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to stabilize the nomenclature according to Article 74 of 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.50608" author="ICZN" journalOrPublisher="The International Trust for Zoological Nomenclature c / o the Natural History Museum, London" pageId="12" pageNumber="381" refId="B10" refString="ICZN, 1999. International Code of Zoological Nomenclature. Fourth Edition. The International Trust for Zoological Nomenclature c/o the Natural History Museum, London, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.50608" title="International Code of Zoological Nomenclature. Fourth Edition." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.50608" year="1999">ICZN (1999)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
